Interview Questions

Q1. What is the Set interface in the Java Collections Framework?
-->Set is an interface in the Java Collections Framework that stores unique elements. It does not allow duplicate elements and is mainly used when uniqueness of data is required.

    Characteristics
    
          Does not allow duplicates.
          Can contain at most one null element (depending on implementation).
          Does not support index-based access.
          HashSet does not maintain insertion order.
          LinkedHashSet maintains insertion order.
          TreeSet stores elements in sorted order.
    
    Example:
        
        import java.util.*;
        
        public class Demo {
            public static void main(String[] args) {
        
                Set<String> set = new HashSet<>();
        
                set.add("Java");
                set.add("Python");
                set.add("Java");
        
                System.out.println(set);
            }
        }
        
        Possible Output
        
        [Java, Python]







Q2. Why does Set not allow duplicate elements?
-->A Set is designed to store only unique elements.

      For implementations like HashSet:
      
      It uses hashCode() to determine the storage location.
      It uses equals() to compare elements.
      If an element already exists, the duplicate is not added.
      
      This ensures uniqueness and prevents duplicate data.




Q3. How does Set work internally?
-->The internal implementation depends on the specific Set class.
      
      HashSet
          Uses a HashMap internally.
          Elements are stored as keys in the HashMap.
          Values are dummy objects.
      LinkedHashSet
          Uses a LinkedHashMap internally.
          Maintains insertion order.
      TreeSet
          Uses a TreeMap internally.
          Stores elements in sorted order using a Red-Black Tree.




Q4. What are the advantages and disadvantages of using Set?
-->Advantages
      Prevents duplicate elements.
      Fast searching (HashSet average O(1)).
      Dynamic size.
      Useful for storing unique data.
      Supports different implementations (HashSet, LinkedHashSet, TreeSet).
   Disadvantages
          No index-based access.
          HashSet does not maintain insertion order.
          TreeSet operations are slower than HashSet (O(log n)).
          Only one null element is allowed in HashSet and LinkedHashSet; TreeSet does not allow null.



Q5. What are the main classes that implement the Set interface?
-->The main implementations are:

    1. HashSet
        Uses a hash table.
        No insertion order.
        Fastest for basic operations.
    2. LinkedHashSet
        Maintains insertion order.
        Slightly slower than HashSet.
    3. TreeSet
        Stores elements in sorted order.
        Uses a Red-Black Tree.
        Does not allow null.

| Class         | Ordering        | Duplicate | Null        | Performance                    |
| ------------- | --------------- | --------- | ----------- | ------------------------------ |
| HashSet       | No              | No        | One `null`  | Fast (`O(1)` average)          |
| LinkedHashSet | Insertion Order | No        | One `null`  | Slightly slower than `HashSet` |
| TreeSet       | Sorted Order    | No        | Not allowed | `O(log n)`                     |



Q6. Can you store null values in a Set?
-->Yes, but it depends on the implementation.

HashSet → Allows one null element.
LinkedHashSet → Allows one null element.
TreeSet → Does not allow null because it compares elements for sorting.

Example:

import java.util.*;

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Set<String> set = new HashSet<>();

        set.add(null);
        set.add("Java");
        set.add(null);

        System.out.println(set);
    }
}

Output

[null, Java]
